postcontent:
M240 Full Metal Airsoft Machine Gun AEG Sqaud Automatic Weapon w/ Box Magazine 

In the late 1970's the US Army adopted a new 7.62mm medium duty machine gun into their ranks: the M240. It was first used as a coaxial machine gun in tanks but slowly made its way to other mounted uses by the late 1980's, the updated model referred to as the M240C. Due to a surplus of M240C's the Army passed some on to the USMC. When the Marines got their hands on the M240C they installed an "infantry modification kit", thus spawning the M240G, the first infantry model of the M240. Having seen the success of the M240G and its effectiveness as a ground mounted 7.62mm machine gun, the US Army decided to test and eventually adopt the M240B, the slightly updated factory production variant of the M240G, into its ranks to replace their outdated M60E4's. Throughout its years of service the M240 has proven itself, in all its variations, to be an effective, reliable medium duty combat machine gun.

postcontent: Recently these rifles have taken a jump in popularity. They are cheap, reliable, and tons of ammo is readily available. But don't pay $150 and more for a run of the mill round receiver with restruck numbers. There's plenty still out there in cosmoline at the gun store for that price. title: For Sale/Trade:  Thank you
postcontent: Thank you guys for all the positive feedback. I really want to thank you all individually but there are a few wolves in sheep's clothing out there. Maybe I'll disclose those I've found later but for now I would like to ask you one simple favor. Just flag one ad. One ad that's overpriced, or if it falls into another catagory just flag it spam because it will be noticed by administration more seriously. I'm just getting started but surely I'll be blocked before too long so please. Show the guys who left and those about to throw in the towel that the shooting community isn't all about a buck. If I can get one shooter that's here for the love of shooting to flag off one ad for every mag of ammo I gave away to bring another person into our sport, then I've done well and gave back again. title: For Sale:  .40 H&K USP Compact
postcontent:
A very well taken care of Heckler & Koch USP Compact .40 caliber hand gun for sale. 
* Original Case 
* Original Documents 
* Extra Clips available at $25/clip 

If you are looking at this gun, you know how good this brand of gun is. Trusted by the most demanding special operatives in the world as their side arm, the H&K USP is the ultimate performer. 

The USP Compact’s machined steel slide features drift adjustable front and rear sights, aggressive grasping grooves and a prominent set of metal sights (both three dot and night sights are available). The generously sized ejection port and a large claw extractor ensure positive extraction and ejection of spent cases while the extractor does double duty as a loaded chamber indicator.

The barrel features polygonal rifling for enhanced accuracy, easier cleaning and longer barrel life. The external hammer has been bobbed so it won’t hang up on clothing or gear—further enhancing conceal-ability.

With the reduction in length of the slide and barrel, the mechanical recoil reduction system found on large-frame USPs was replaced by a flat compression spring contained in the captive recoil spring assembly by a polymer absorber bushing. Despite the part’s smaller size, service life is still engineered to exceed 20,000 rounds.

The slide reciprocates on four steel inserts that are integral to the fiber-reinforced polymer frame. To make it southpaw-friendly, the pistol’s magazine release paddle is located at the base of the trigger guard where it can be activated by either hand. The slide release is well shaped and positioned for easy manipulation and the control lever (a.k.a. safety/de-cocker lever) can be mounted on either side, although moving it to the starboard does require additional components.

The design of the pistol’s lockwork allows it to be carried in either “cocked and locked” mode or with the hammer down on a loaded chamber. For the former, you chamber a round and then push the control lever up to make the pistol “safe.” Pushing the lever down allows you to fire the pistol with a short, single-action trigger stoke.

For the latter, you chamber a round and then exert additional pressure on the control lever, pushing it past the “fire” position where it safely de-cocks the pistol. You can then fire the first round with a double-action trigger pull and subsequent shots in single-action.
The breech is locked by the barrel hood moving up into and bearing on the front edge of the ejection port. When you fire the pistol, the slide/barrel unit reciprocates to the rear locked together. After a short distance the barrel is cammed down, which allows the slide to continue rearward extracting and ejecting the spent cartridge case. The recoil spring then pulls the slide forward, stripping the next round from the magazine and chambering it. As the slide goes into battery the barrel is cammed up, locking it and the slide together again.

- See more at: http://www.personaldefenseworld.com/2012/10/heckler-koch-usp-compact-40/2/#hk_usp_compact40-0201_phatchfinal

title: For Sale:  Springfield Ultra Compact: Stainless Commander 1911 in .45
location: Leesburg, Sterling, Chantilly, Northern Virginia, Virginia
postcontent:
Once again, my sad effort to try and like 3" 1911's ends in a sale/trade. This little beauty is a 2nd owner gun with less than 200 down the pipe - 100 my own. I've really tried to like 3" 1911's, and they just are appealing, perfectly weighted, and in the ever manly .45acp. Maybe that's the problem. Maybe I'm not man enough. I was measured, and came up wanting. Maybe you're man enough to tame this little stallion. 

OK, my sad little parable aside, this is a great 3" 1911, if that's your thing. Or want to make it your thing. This could be your carry gun, it could be your truck gun, or your nightstand gun. For me, it was just my range gun. And I just can't shoot a 3" 1911 at 25 yards the same way I can with a 5" 1911. And if I can't shoot a gun the way I want, then I won't shoot it at all. 

Gun comes with the three mags. The ammo is my own brew of match ammo, so they wont. If you would like to leave 2 of the mags behind with me, I'm happy to knock some off the price.

title: For Sale:  5kW (6.6+kW) Diesel Power Plant MEP-002A Onan Generator
postcontent:
Lose power? Want to be ready for the next outage with clean, reliable, backup power that can support your home for weeks? 

I've lived in the Fox Valley for several years, it seems on average we lose power at least once each year. 

This is an Libby Corporation MEP-002A Military Diesel Generator. It's a baby with only 92 hours of use, stored indoors almost it's entire life and, very well taken care of by the WI Army National Guard. 

92 hours of use, I wanted to repeat that. These machines are renowned for lasting tens of thousands of hours. 

For decades, Libby Corp has ruggedized (militarized) dependable Onan Diesel Generators for use around the world under the extreme conditions demanded by the US military. This machine is incredibly overbuilt and designed for continuous use in temperatures from -20*F to +120*F. In comparison most commercial generators today are designed for temporary use, and need to be shut down repeatedly to avoid damage and overheating. This machine will run continuously for tens of thousands of hours if fueled, and only needs to be shut down for servicing oil and filters. 

The machine is a 6.6kW Onan Twin Cylinder Cast Iron Diesel Generator mounted on an Aluminum Skid with dual heavy duty batteries, a 6.75 gallon fuel tank, and a 24v control system. 

Military Spec Fuel System: 
This machine has a total of three fuel pumps, four fuel screens, two fuel filters, and a fuel strainer. Two redundant fuel filters in addition to a fuel strainer, are mounted on the frame for easy servicing. Two redundant fuel pumps with a third auxiliary fuel pump are mounted under the control box for use with an external fuel source. Each fuel pump also has a serviceable fuel screen built into it's base, and in addition there is a screen in the fuel tank's opening. The in-line fuel pumps are designed so that if one fails the other continues to pump through its carcass keeping the generator operational in extreme conditions. The fuel system is designed to operate using JP-8 or Diesel, and it is specifically designed to be able to run in unfortunate circumstances with contaminated fuel, hence the filtration system. The auxiliary fuel pump is designed to pull fuel from an external source like a fuel can, I use an external 30 gallon diesel tank. The generator has a bong adapter for fuel drums which is included. Fuel consumption for this machine is .30 gallons of diesel per hour at half load and just under .5 gal/hr at full load. 

24v Electrical System:
The generator itself operates off two on board heavy duty 12v batteries mounted in a corrosion resistant stainless steel cage on the side of the skid. The generator operates off a 24v system with a slave receptacle under the control box for easy jumping from any other 24v source. The control panel has two 24v lights which illuminate the gauges and switches for night time use. The generator has its own 24v charging system on board which maintains the batteries while the generator is in use. 

6.6kW of continuous power:
Unlike it's commercial counterparts this generator is designed for use in several configurations without the need to rewire it's control box. The generator has a master switch which changes the output from 120v/1ph(55A) to 240v/1ph(27.5A) to 208v/3ph(31A). Yes this machine is switchable between 120v/240v/208v with the turn of a knob, no need to rewire it's internals. It is perfect for powering industrial machinery requiring three phase 208v power, or simply for providing residential backup at 240v. The Military underrates their MEP equipment so that it can be used in all climates and at all altitudes. The data label on this unit reads 5kW, and it is capable of outputting 5kW continuously all around the world. The % load gauge on the control panel reads between 0% and 133% and the unit is fully capable of exceeding 6.6kW of output in this Wisconsin climate. For example when I load test this machine with a 4,500 watt inductive load at 15*F, just above sea level here in Appleton WI, the % load gauge reads at a mere 60%. 

Onan Diesel Engine:
These things run forever. At 1800 rpm Onan diesels like this operate at half the speed of most commercial diesel generators, doubling their life expectancy and reducing noise output. This machine has a very heavy duty twin cylinder air cooled 1147cc engine. By being air cooled you don't have to worry about maintaining engine coolant or worrying about gasket leaks. The engine has a mechanical oil pressure gauge, a low oil pressure shut off safety feature, and an industrial oil cooler designed into it's air cooling system. The engine has its own electric start with a cold weather valve on the air intake system to aid the glow plugs in heating intake air during cold weather operation. The air cooling system on this engine has a temperature controlled shroud which opens louvers near the exhaust at a variable rate to ensure stable and consistent temperature control of the engine. 

This Generator is in extremely good condition. I have recently completely serviced the engine, replaced all filters, changed the oil, and completed an annual flush of the fuel system. The batteries are in great shape as I keep them maintained with a battery tender. 

This is a perfect machine for providing reliable off-grid power. I have another that I use to provide 55 Amp service to our cabin up north which doesn't have electricity. 

If you are interested I can schedule a demonstration and you can experience a load test of this awesome machine.

92 hours on the meter, almost brand new.
